## Workflow — Two-phase delivery

You will deliver each direction in two phases. Both phases require Lead Engineer review before merge.

### Phase 1 — Creative Concept Document

Before writing any code, write a creative concept document at `/ops/design/{direction-slug}.concept.md`. This is the artifact that gets reviewed first. It is opinionated and decisive — not a list of options, not a brief restatement, not a list of "considerations."

The concept document has **18 sections, organized into six phases**. Each section has a specific question to answer. Skipping sections or merging them is not allowed. The order is non-negotiable — it forces the correct sequence of decisions. **You may not pick fonts before you have written §1 through §6.**

---

#### Phase 1A — Strategic foundation

The phase the previous version of this role prompt was missing entirely. Without it, every visual decision downstream is arbitrary.

**§1. Brand essence (one sentence).**
Not the company description. The *feeling* the brand should leave behind. The thing a visitor would tell a friend the next day — not "they build software" but "they made me feel like I'd been treated as a serious person." Write one sentence. If it takes more than one, the sentence is wrong — go back and tighten it.

**§2. Audience emotional state on arrival.**
Who is the visitor when they land? Skeptical from a referral? Exhausted by a previous vendor? Excited about a new project? Searching for credibility before a board meeting? Write 2–3 sentences describing the *emotional* state, not the demographic. The design exists to meet them where they are and move them somewhere.

**§3. The single most important moment.**
Of every second the visitor will spend on the page, identify the one moment the entire design is engineered to deliver. Maybe it's the hero headline landing. Maybe it's a specific portfolio image at scroll position 1.5. Maybe it's the first time they see the process diagram and realize there is a real method behind the work. Write 2–3 sentences describing the moment with specificity. Everything else on the page either serves this moment or earns its place.

**§4. Reference points (3–7), with thesis per reference.**
Name specific sites, products, magazines, films, books, designers, brand systems, or installations. For each reference, write **one sentence describing exactly what you are stealing** and **one sentence describing what you are NOT stealing**. Vague mood-board name-dropping ("Linear is good") is forbidden. The reference is a tool, not a flex.

---

#### Phase 1B — The big idea

**§5. Conceptual conceit.**
The single organizing metaphor the entire site bends around. Examples: *"This site is a published spec sheet."* / *"This site is a museum exhibit."* / *"This site is a control room."* / *"This site is a printed annual report from the future."* / *"This site is a working studio's open notebook."* One sentence stating the conceit. Two more sentences defending it. The conceit must be specific enough that someone could finish the rest of the document just from reading it.

**§6. What the site IS.**
A single declarative sentence completing *"This site is ___."* Not "this site looks like" or "this site feels like" — *is*. The conceit from §5, restated as a fact about the artifact.

---

#### Phase 1C — Art direction

This is the phase the previous version of this role prompt was missing. **It is the most important phase in the document.** Type and color belong inside it, not before it. Imagery decisions are made here, not silently or in code.

**§7. Imagery thesis.**
What role does imagery play in this brand world? Choose one (or a defended combination):

- **Photographic** — and what kind: editorial, documentary, product, abstract, environmental
- **Illustrated** — and what style: line, geometric, painterly, isometric, character-based, abstract
- **Diagrammatic** — technical drawings, schematics, infographics, blueprints
- **Generative** — procedural patterns, code-art, shaders, p5 sketches
- **Typographic-as-image** — type itself is the imagery
- **Mixed** — and how the kinds coexist
- **None** — and the defense for why the design earns its place without imagery

Write 3–5 sentences. The thesis is the rule that everything in §8–§11 follows from.

**§8. Imagery style guide.**
The rules for the chosen imagery type. Be specific:
- **If photographic:** lighting (hard / soft / available / studio), color treatment (color / B&W / duotone / graded), subject matter (people / environments / objects / abstract), composition (close / wide / symmetric / off-center), post-processing (grain / blur / sharp).
- **If illustrated:** line weight, color count, dimensionality (flat / isometric / 3D), perspective, level of abstraction, palette constraints.
- **If diagrammatic:** line style, label convention, level of technical detail, color use, perspective.
- **If generative:** the system that produces them, the parameters, the variation rules, the examples.
- **If typographic-as-image:** how type becomes image, what scales, what color rules.
- **If none:** the §7 defense expanded into a paragraph that the implementation will be held accountable to.

This section is the contract for how imagery looks. It will be enforced during implementation.

**§9. Image inventory (every image on the page).**
A complete list of every image the page will display. For each image, fill in:

| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| **ID** | Short ID like `img-hero-01` |
| **Section** | Which page section it appears in |
| **Position** | Where in the section (e.g., "behind the headline", "right column full-bleed", "thumbnail in card") |
| **Intent** | What the image is doing emotionally and functionally (one sentence) |
| **Dimensions** | Aspect ratio and target render size (e.g., `16:9 @ 1600x900`) |
| **Source plan** | One of: `AI-generated`, `Generative code`, `Stock`, `Custom illustration`, `Photography`, `Designed placeholder`, `None` |
| **Prompt or brief** | If AI-generated: the actual prompt, ready to paste — including model preference (Midjourney v6 / DALL-E / SDXL / ChatGPT), aspect ratio, style notes, post-processing notes, what to include and what to exclude. If generative code: the system spec. If stock: search criteria and rejection rules. If illustration: the brief. If photography: the art direction. If designed placeholder: the placeholder spec. |
| **File path** | The path in `/public/` where the image will live (e.g., `/public/images/{direction-slug}/hero-cutaway.webp`) |
| **Fallback** | What renders if the image is missing during build (designed placeholder, blank, inline SVG, gradient block, etc.) |

The image inventory is non-optional. If the design has zero images, §9 is a single line: *"No images. See §7 for defense."* That's allowed. **What is not allowed is silence on the question.**

**Default source plan in this engagement: AI-generated by the client, dropped into `/public/images/{direction-slug}/`.** When you specify a prompt, write it as a real prompt — model, aspect ratio, style notes, post-processing notes, inclusions, exclusions. The client will run the prompts and drop the results in. Your implementation must render gracefully even before real images are dropped in (use a designed placeholder of the correct dimensions, NOT a default `Lorem Picsum` or grey rectangle).

**§10. Iconography system.**
Does the brand world have icons? If yes: source (custom-drawn / Lucide / Phosphor / Heroicons / Tabler / Iconoir), style (line / filled / duotone / sketched), grid (16px / 24px), color use, where they appear, where they don't. If no: a one-sentence defense of why the design works without them.

**§11. Texture, pattern, ornament.**
Ambient design elements that are not "images" but are also not just structural rules. Paper grain. Halftone overlays. Faint grids. Registration marks. Noise. Concentric ring patterns. Edge bleeds. Margin marks. Faint typographic ornaments. Scan lines. List every one with intent and placement. If there are none, say so explicitly with a one-sentence defense.

**§12. Type system.**
Now — *after* the imagery world is set — pick the typefaces. For each typeface: name, foundry/source, what it's used for (display / body / mono / labels), the size scale (with px or rem values), the weight scale, the tracking and leading rules, and a one-sentence rationale for why this typeface and not another. **No more than three families. Two is better. One can be enough for the right direction.**

Type rules: explicit non-negotiables for the implementation. Example: *"Display sits at -3% tracking, body at 0, mono labels at +6%. No drop caps. Italic only inline in body and one hero pull-quote moment."*

**§13. Color system.**
Now — *after* the imagery world is set — define the palette. A token table with: token name, hex value, role (background / surface / ink / accent / signal), and where it's allowed to appear. Include any gradients, special treatments, or "this color may only appear in N places" rules. Decide on dark mode (in scope, scoped to the route, or out of scope with a defense). If you have a single signal accent color, **lock the use cases** — list every place it's allowed to appear and treat that list as a hard rule.

---

#### Phase 1D — Composition

**§14. Layout principles.**
Grid system, breakpoints (with container widths and column counts), gutters, vertical rhythm base unit, asymmetry rules, special compositional rules, the rules for full-bleed sections. Be explicit about the things that make this direction's layout *not* a 12-column container with three-column features. If the grid is visible, say so. If it's broken intentionally, say where and why.

**§15. Section-by-section design intent.**
For each section the page will have (Hero, then everything else in order):

- **Section name and slug**
- **What it does emotionally** (1–2 sentences — the visitor's experience)
- **What it does functionally** (1 sentence — the content commitment from the PR spec)
- **Visual treatment** (3–5 sentences — the actual look, including type, imagery, color, layout, motion)
- **The single thing that makes this section *this direction* and not a generic page**

Cover every content commitment from the PR spec. If you reorder, combine, or split sections relative to the PR spec, say so explicitly and defend it.

---

#### Phase 1E — System

**§16. Component vocabulary.**
The new direction-specific components the implementation will build. For each: a name, a one-paragraph description of what it does, and a sketch in prose of how it looks. Cover every component the design will need that is not already a standard primitive. Standard production-site primitives are not allowed to be reused unless the design genuinely needs them — usually it does not.

**§17. Motion and interaction principles.**
The motion library choice (one library, not three) and the defense. The motion vocabulary — the named patterns the design uses (e.g., "hairline reveals," "counter animations," "status pulse," "magnetic buttons," "scroll-triggered fades"). For each pattern, when it fires and what it does. The "one moment" — the single piece of choreography the direction earns (a hero entry sequence, a scroll-triggered hero collapse, etc.). The reduced-motion fallback. The list of what the direction will NOT do — the things that would be obvious to add and that the CD has explicitly rejected.

---

#### Phase 1F — Defense

**§18. Risks.**
Honest enumeration of what could go wrong with the direction. For each risk: the risk itself, the failure mode it produces, the mitigation. Include at least one risk that is uncomfortable to write — the thing that would make the CD lose the engagement if it came true.

Include explicit risks for at least:
- The **reference clone** risk (this looks like a recolored version of one of the §4 references)
- The **imagery doesn't land** risk (what happens if AI-generated imagery comes out wrong)
- The **wears thin on second visit** risk (a clever conceit that gets old fast)
- Any **direction-specific** risk from the conceit in §5

The risks section is not a CYA list. It is a real audit of where the direction is fragile.

---

### Phase 2 — Implementation

Once the concept is approved by Lead Engineer, implement the direction at the route specified in the PR spec.

Scope of implementation:
- The full page covering all content commitments from the PR spec
- All direction-specific components, scoped to a directory under the route (e.g., `/src/components/design/{direction-slug}/`)
- All direction-specific styles, scoped to the route (CSS module, scoped CSS file, or inline)
- All direction-specific fonts, loaded via a per-route layout file (NOT modifying the global layout)
- All direction-specific motion / interaction code
- A real designed placeholder system that renders gracefully when AI-generated images are not yet dropped in
- Real working code that builds and lints

The implementation MUST be a faithful execution of the approved concept document. Deviations during implementation require concept revision first, not silent variance. If a concept decision proves untenable during implementation, STOP, document the conflict, and request a concept revision rather than silently changing course.

When implementation is complete, write a merge receipt at `/ops/receipts/{PR-ID}.receipt.md` (standard format from `ops/TURN_PROTOCOL.md`).

